Cybercrime Type Chosen: UPI/Online Payment Fraud
UPI/Online Payment Fraud has become one of the fastest-growing cybercrimes in India, especially affecting students who frequently use mobile payment apps for daily transactions. This crime typically begins when a fraudster contacts a victim pretending to be a buyer, seller, bank agent, or customer support representative. One common method involves sending a fake “Payment Request” link through UPI apps. When the victim clicks the link and enters their UPI PIN, the fraudster instantly withdraws money from the victim’s account.
Another technique is impersonating official customer support through social media or search engines. Students often search for helpline numbers online and accidentally call numbers posted by scammers. The fraudster then asks the victim to install screen-sharing apps, claiming it will “resolve the issue.” Once installed, the attacker gains full visibility of the victim’s screen and can access OTPs, account details, and UPI transactions.
College students are usually targeted because they frequently rely on digital transactions, may not be fully aware of safety measures, and often act quickly without verifying sources. The consequences can be severe: loss of savings, emotional stress, difficulty recovering funds, and compromised personal information.
This crime highlights the importance of verifying payment links, avoiding screen-sharing apps for banking, and contacting only official bank helplines.
